\begin_layout Subsection
Proposed algorithm
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We identified three important causes that are present in the unacceptable
 recordings: 1) flatlines, 2) spikes and 3) steps.
 Then a finer detection is performed using feature extraction and a machine
 learning algorithm.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Flatline detector
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For detecting the inactivity of a lead, we developed 3 algorithms that analyse
 the variance, the derivative and the signal amplitude in order to implement
 the best performing approach: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
FL1=min\left\{ var(\mathrm{\mathbf{S_{i}}})\right\} \:\:\:\:\:\:\:\:\:\:FL2=min\left\{ mean\left(\frac{d\mathrm{\mathbf{S_{i}}}}{dt}\right)\right\} \:\:\:\:\:\:\:\:\:\:{\displaystyle FL3=min\left\{ \left|\boldsymbol{S_{i}}-mean(\boldsymbol{S_{i}})\right|\right\} }
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The multilead ECG signal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{S_{i}}}$
\end_inset

 in the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

, which starts at the i
\emph on
-th
\emph default
 sample.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 interval was adopted of 1.5 seconds length, this restriction makes unlikely
 to produce false detections in heart rates above 40 bpm.
 We analysed the ROC curves by sweeping the threshold value for each 
\begin_inset Formula $FLx$
\end_inset

 flatline detector.
 In Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:FL-ROC"

\end_inset

, It can be seen that the 
\begin_inset Formula $FL2$
\end_inset

 is the best performing estimator with best response getting 
\begin_inset Formula $99.17\%$
\end_inset

 of true positives and 
\begin_inset Formula $0\%$
\end_inset

 of false negatives with a threshold value of 
\begin_inset Formula $0.85\,\nicefrac{mV}{sec}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

