\begin_layout Subsubsection
SQI based detector
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the implementation of the detector we used the SQI features model described
 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "clifford-quality-cinc,behar-quality,liq-multilevel"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The features model is composed of twelve SQI per lead (pSQI, basSQI, bsSQI,
 eSQI, hfSQI, bSQI, sSQI, kSQI, rsdSQI, purSQI, entSQI and pcaSQI ) resulting
 in a total of 144 features per 10 seconds segment described in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "clifford-quality-cinc,behar-quality,liq-multilevel"

\end_inset

.
 In this work, we analysed some variants of the bSQI feature, which is the
 ratio of the heartbeats detected by a robust QRS detector to the amount
 detected by a simple detector.
 The studied variants are: bSQI1: sqrs - wqrs, bSQI2: gqrs - wqrs, bSQI3:
 wqrs - wavedet, bSQI4: sqrs - wavedet, bSQI5: gqrs - wavedet and bSQI6:
 gqrs - sqrs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Following the methodologies adopted in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "clifford-quality-cinc,behar-quality,liq-multilevel"

\end_inset

, a support vector machine with Gaussian kernel was used as detector.
 From these features, we train two models: a reduced model (RD) which only
 uses 6 of the 12 SQIs (kSQI, sSQI, pSQI, basSQI, bSQI and pcaSQI) as in
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "behar-quality"

\end_inset

 and other which uses all (FD) the features.
\end_layout

