\begin_layout Standard
In this work, we evaluated an algorithm for the quantification of the ECG
 quality based on a binary tree (BT) followed by an SQI detector with a
 full (FD) and reduced (RD) set of features.
 In Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Performance-of-bSQIs-1"

\end_inset

 we presented the results of evaluating the individual contribution of each
 bSQI alone.
 The bSQI2 feature achieved the best individual performance, suggesting
 that QRS detectors 
\emph on
gqrs
\emph default
 and 
\emph on
wqrs
\emph default
 are the most appropriate to calculate this feature.
 Then we evaluated the performance of the BT alone, comparing the detector
 combinations shown in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:FinalPerformance"

\end_inset

.
 We found that the SK detector does not produce an increase of the BT performanc
e, resulting FL-HI the best combination for the BT alone.
 This could be explained because of the scarcity of spikes found in the
 databases used in these work.
 These aspect should be further evaluated in other databases, and eventually
 removed if these results are corroborated.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The SQI models FD and RD achieved the best accuracy and sensitivity when
 evaluated alone.
 When we evaluated the combination of BT-RD and BT-FD, a decrease in performance
 was obtained.
 One reason that could explain this fact is the criterion used to label
 the ecgqdb.
 We found many unacceptable (according to our criterion) records which contain
 flatline or huge impulses, which were labelled as acceptable.
 The best accuracy and sensitivity was obtained by the full detector based
 in SQI with almost a 94% of accuracy and 99% of sensitivity, followed by
 the RD with a accuracy of 93% and sensitivity of 98%.
 The best specificity was obtained by BT-RD with 88% followed by BT-FD with
 87%.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In following works, we consider that improvements should be performed in
 the features model and in the labelling quality of the databases used.
 Other aspect to improve, is to increase the amount of data used, in order
 to evaluate the generalization capability of the algorithms.
 As a result of this work, an algorithm for the quantification of the ECG
 quality was developed, with a performance comparable to the state of the
 art.
\end_layout

